'''Cey Adams''' (b. New York, 1962) is a visual artist, graphic designer and author. He was the founding creative director of [[Def Jam Recordings]] and is known for his work with [[Beastie Boys]], [[Public Enemy (group)|Public Enemy]], [[LL Cool J]], [[Jay-Z]], and [[Mary J. Blige]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/explore/inside_out/2011/04/28/cey-adams-an-insiders-look-at-hip-hop-culture|title=MoMA {{!}} Cey Adams: An Insider’s Look at Hip-hop Culture|website=www.moma.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> He has been described as "legendary" for his work in hip-hop [[graphic design]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://antisociety.com/the-man-behind-the-curtain-cey-adams/|title=ANTISOCIETY.COM  » Blog Archive   » The Man Behind The Curtain: Cey Adams|website=antisociety.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

==Biography==
Adams was a [[graffiti artist]] in the late 70s and early 80s. He studied painting at New York's [[School of Visual Arts]] and ultimately had work exhibited in the city alongside [[Jean Michel Basquiat]] and [[Keith Haring]]. In 1982 he appeared in the historic [[PBS]] documentary [[Style Wars]] about subway graffiti in New York.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.brooklynartscouncil.org/documents/2452|title=Honoree: Cey Adams|website=Brooklyn Arts Council|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Style Wars (TV Movie 1983)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0177262/fullcredits|accessdate=2018-01-13}}</ref>

Cey Adams met [[Ad-Rock|Adam Horovitz]] in 1983 and a close relationship with the [[Beastie Boys]] began with Adams designing the graffiti lettering that spelled out the name of the band on the cover of their [[12" single]] for [[Cooky Puss]]. Around the same time he began working with [[Russell Simmons]]' [[Rush Communications|Rush Artist Management]] creating logos, tour merchandising, billboards and advertising campaigns for rap artists including Beastie Boys, [[Run DMC]], [[De La Soul]] and LL Cool J.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.beastiemania.com/whois/adams_cey/|title=Beastiemania.com - Who Is Who - Cey Adams|last=Pollicino|first=Raul|website=www.beastiemania.com|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicfanclubs.org/beastieboys/ceyadams.htm|title=Beastie Boys \ Interview with Cey Adams, member of the Beastie Boys family|website=www.musicfanclubs.org|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

In the late 80s Adams and his partner [[Steve Carr]] co-founded the Drawing Board, Def Jam Recording's in-house visual design firm overseeing the [[visual style]] of Def Jam’s artists as well as artists signed to [[MCA Records|MCA]], [[Universal Music Group|Universal]], [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]], [[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]] and [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]].

The Drawing Board closed in 1999 and Adams began working on corporate advertising campaigns for companies such as [[Levi’s]], [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[HBO]], [[Coca-Cola]], [[Burton Snowboards]], [[Moët & Chandon]], [[Comedy Central]], [[HBO]], and Warner Bros.

==After Def Jam==
Adams continued designing branding and logos, working with companies such as Revolver Films and [[Asylum Records]], and music artists as diverse as [[Foo Fighters]], [[Don Henley]], and Mary J. Blige.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2016/01/27/interview-original-def-jam-creative-director-cey-adams-talks-latest-works/|title=ORIGINAL DEF JAM CREATIVE DIRECTOR CEY ADAMS TALKS LATEST WORKS|last=Eustice|first=Kyle|date=2018-01-13|website=The Source|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

From 1999 - 2000 Adams worked as a creative director for Urban Magic, an internet startup founded by [[Magic Johnson]] and [[Starbucks]] chairman [[Howard Schultz]].

In 2000 he co-designed the hip-hop wing of [[Seattle]]'s [[Experience Music Project]]. In 2001 [[Dave Chappelle]] hired Adams to create the logo for his new sketch comedy show, "[[Chappelle's Show]]" on [[Comedy Central]].

Having previously designed clothes for [[Run DMC]] for [[Adidas]], in 2006 he was commissioned to design his own custom track suits and sneakers featuring Beastie Boys. In 2007 he created a limited edition collection for [[Muhammad Ali]] for Adidas. The shoes were included as part of “The Rise of Sneaker Culture” exhibit at the [[Brooklyn Museum of Art]] in New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sneakerfreaker.com/articles/ceyadamsdefjamandbilladlerinterview/|title=Cey Adams (Defjam) & Bill Adler Hip Hop Art Book  - Sneaker Freaker|last=DotDev|date=2008-09-09|work=Sneaker Freaker|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-au}}</ref>

In 2008 Adams co-edited "DEFinition: the Art and Design of Hip-Hop", published by [[Harper Collins]], with the music journalist [[Bill Adler]], who had been Def Jam's original publicist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.papermag.com/the-12-new-art-shows-to-see-this-week-1427574000.html|title=The 12 New Art Shows to See This Week|date=2015-05-20|work=PAPERMAG|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://globalgrind.cassiuslife.com/1723493/seminal-graphic-designer-cey-adams-def-jam-first-25-years-last-great-record-label/|title=Seminal Graphic Designer Cey Adams "On Def Jam: The First 25 Years Of The Last Great Record Label"|date=2011-09-20|work=Global Grind|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.7283/title.cey-adams-and-bill-adler-create-hip-hop-art-book#|title=Cey Adams And Bill Adler Create Hip Hop Art Book|last=http://hiphopdx.com|first=HipHopDX -|work=HipHopDX|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpercollins.com/authors/32681|title=Cey Adams|website=HarperCollins US|language=en|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hiphopdx.com/videos/id.24644/title.original-def-jam-creative-director-cey-adams-to-appear-in-docu-series-about-his-book-definition#|title=Original Def Jam Creative Director Cey Adams To Appear In Docu-Series About His Book "DEFinition"|last=http://hiphopdx.com|first=HipHopDX -|work=HipHopDX|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US}}</ref>

Adams was invited to participate in Looking at Music 3.0 at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York in 2011. It was the third in a series of exhibitions exploring the influence of music on contemporary art practices, focusing on New York in the 1980s and 1990s. He also designed a poster for the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/explore/inside_out/2011/04/28/cey-adams-an-insiders-look-at-hip-hop-culture/|title=MoMA {{!}} Cey Adams: An Insider’s Look at Hip-hop Culture|website=www.moma.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

That same year, [[Rizzoli (book imprint)|Rizzoli]] published "Def Jam Recordings: The First 25 Years of the Last Great Record Label" Adams designed the book and CD box collection for this "comprehensive coffee table book that compiled over two decades of photos, album artwork, and stories behind every record released under the label."Also in 2011 he designed [[Tommy Boy Records]]' 30th anniversary poster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thelaunchmagazine.com/?p=246|title=BOOK REVIEW:  ‘Def Jam Recordings: The First 25 Years of the Last Great Record Label’ by Bill Adler, Dan Charnas, Rick Rubin (Preface), Russell Simmons (Preface) «  thelaunchmagazine.com|website=thelaunchmagazine.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

In celebration of [[Martin Luther King Day]] in 2013, Adams was commissioned by [[The Juilliard School]] to paint a large scale [[mural]] titled "Dream," a powerful portrait of Dr. King and a visual timeline of the [[Civil Rights Movement]]. He also worked with [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]] on "Picture the Dream,” a community-based creative workshop which teaches young people the value of making art while educating them about Dr. King's message of equality through non-violence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://amsterdamnews.com/news/2012/jan/19/bam-celebrates-kings-day/|title=BAM celebrates King's day|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

Adams took a two-month residency at the [[Bemis Center for Contemporary Arts]] in [[Omaha]], [[Nebraska]], in 2014, during which time he also created a mural with local teenagers, with the message "Love", and in an interview with the Omaha World Herald talks about developing his new series of artworks referencing classic corporate logos. In his recent artworks, Adams employs mixed media including hand-made papers and magazine clippings on canvas, and silk screening.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.omaha.com/go/q-a-def-jam-founding-designer-on-omaha-work-at/article_bf85f087-c6dd-5362-a443-cc58025e3360.html|title=Q&A: Def Jam founding designer on Omaha, work at Bemis Center|last=writer|first=Casey Logan / World-Herald staff|work=Omaha.com|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en}}</ref>

In March, 2015, a new body of collage work incorporating the corporate logos was exhibited at [http://rushphilanthropic.org/ Rush Philanthropic Arts Foundation], an organization "dedicated to providing inner city youth across New York City with significant exposure to the arts." It was founded in 1995 by [[Russell Simmons]]. The Foundation writes that Adams "draws inspiration from 60’s pop art, sign painting, comic books, and popular culture. His work focuses on themes including pop culture, race and gender relations, cultural and community issues. ''Trusted Brands'' transforms images and icographics that he grew up with." Adams describes the ''Trusted Brands'' series as "an homage to pop art." In an interview with [[NY1]], the director of Rush Art Galleries speaks about Adam's positive influence and advocacy for emerging artists.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2015/03/16/artist-of-iconic-def-jam-album-covers-pays-homage-to-pop-art.html|title=Artist of Iconic Def Jam Album Covers Pays Homage to Pop Art|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailyfreepress.com/2017/09/07/new-cultural-playground-park-in-south-end-south-boston-set-to-open-saturday/|title=dailyfreepress.com/2017/09/07/new-cultural-playground-park-in-south-end-south-boston-set-to-open-saturday/|website=dailyfreepress.com|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

Adams took part in “[http://www.artserve.org/redeye/ Red Eye],” an annual weeks-long exhibition of art and entertainment in [[Fort Lauderdale]], in July 2015. He collaborated with local students, helping them create a mural for the [[National Urban League]] conference, as well as teaching, and lecturing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/business/tourism/fl-urban-league-art-gallery-20150728-story.html|title=Local artists on display at National Urban League Conference|last=Satchell|first=Arlene|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150803022956/http://www.wsvn.com/story/29644133/def-jam-local-artists-create-mural-for-urban-league|title=Def Jam, local artists create mural for Urban League - WSVN-TV - 7NEWS Miami Ft. Lauderdale News, Weather, Deco|date=2015-08-03|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

The [[National Museum of African American History and Culture|Smithsonian’s National Museum of African American History and Culture]] opened in September, 2016 and Adams contributed a wall mural for the opening festival “Freedom Sounds: A Community Celebration.”  Adams also designed a coffee table book published by the Smithsonian that is a 300-page anthology of Hip-Hop that includes a box set of CDs and never-before-seen photographs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2017/11/16/smithsonians-hip-hop-anthology-exceeds-kickstarter-goal/|title=Smithsonian’s Hip-Hop Anthology exceeds Kickstarter goal|last=McGlone|first=Peggy|date=2017-11-16|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://insider.si.edu/2017/10/kickstarter-campaign-create-smithsonian-anthology-hip-hop-rap/|title=The Smithsonian needs your help to make Hip-Hop history!|date=2017-10-18|work=Smithsonian Insider|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://start.lesechos.fr/continuer-etudes/vie-etudiante/5-livres-qui-vont-vous-inspirer-en-2018-10619.php|title=5 livres qui vont vous inspirer en 2018|work=start.lesechos.fr|access-date=2018-01-13|language=fr-FR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.actualitte.com/article/patrimoine-education/le-smithsonian-publie-une-enorme-anthologie-du-hip-hop-americain/86548|title=Le Smithsonian publie une énorme anthologie du hip hop américain|access-date=2018-01-13|language=fr-FR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nmaahc.si.edu/about/news/three-day-festival-celebrates-grand-opening-national-museum-african-american-history-and|title=Three-Day Festival Celebrates the Grand Opening of the National Museum of African American History and Culture|date=2016-09-07|work=National Museum of African American History and Culture|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ksfr.org/post/artist-cey-adams-opening-national-museum-african-american-history-and-culture|title=Artist Cey Adams on the Opening of the National Museum of African American History and Culture|last=Berkovitch|first=Ellen|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thevinylfactory.com/news/smithsonian-institute-anthology-hip-hop-rap/|title=Smithsonian Institute [sic] announces 300-page Anthology of Hip-Hop and Rap|date=2017-10-19|work=The Vinyl Factory|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US}}</ref>

Beyond Walls is a group of [[Lynn, Massachusetts]] residents, business owners, and public art and place-making enthusiasts attempting to create a sense of "place and safety" in Downtown Lynn. Adams completed a mural for this project in July, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itemlive.com/2017/07/17/def-jam-comes-to-downtown-lynn/|title=Def Jam comes to downtown Lynn - Itemlive|date=2017-07-17|work=Itemlive|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wbur.org/artery/2017/07/13/lynn-mural-festival|title=With 15 New Murals In 10 Days, Lynn Wants To Show It's Moved Beyond Its Negative Reputation|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

Adams was the [[Brooklyn Arts Council Film and Video Festival|Brooklyn Arts Council]]'s 2015 50th Anniversary Gala Honoree.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.brooklynartscouncil.org/documents/2483|title=Alive With Art 2015|website=Brooklyn Arts Council|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

Honoring the 44th anniversary of the birth of Hop Hip on August 11, 2017, Google launched a “first-of-its-kind Doodle featuring a custom logo graphic by famed graffiti artist Cey Adams, interactive [[turntables]] on which users can mix samples from legendary tracks, and a serving of Hip Hop history - with an emphasis on its founding pioneers."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/comic-riffs/wp/2017/08/11/google-creates-a-truly-epic-interactive-doodle-to-celebrate-hip-hops-44th-birthday-jam/|title=Hip-hop history: Google creates epic musical Doodle to kick off 44th birthday jam|last=Cavna|first=Michael|date=2017-08-11|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/new-google-doodle-honors-hip-hops-history-2017-8|title=Google's latest Doodle puts you in the DJ booth while paying tribute to hip-hop's history|work=Business Insider|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en}}</ref>

In collaboration with photographer [[Janette Beckman]], Adams worked on a project called the "Mash Up" where graffiti artists "[[Remix|remixed]]" Beckman’s photographs of hip hop musicians, that was released as a book in 2018.<ref>[http://www.fox5ny.com/news/-the-mash-up-remixes-hip-hop-photos-with-graffiti Fox 5 “'The Mash Up' remixes hip-hop photos with graffiti”]</ref><ref>[https://hatandbeard.com/products/the-mash-up-hip-hop-photos-remixed-by-iconic-graffiti-artists Hat and Beard Press]</ref>

For the launch of [[Levi_Strauss_%26_Co.|Levi’s]] new store in Times Square in November, 2018, Adams [[screen-printed]] and [[Airbrush|airbrushed]] clothing. <ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/levis-times-square-flagship-opens-ipo-1162066 “Levi’s Takes Customization to the Next Level With New Times Square Flagship”]</ref>

